Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My motivation stems from the challenge of learning interpretable, sentiment-aware topics in a fully differentiable framework. Existing topic models like LDA or even neural variants (e.g., NVDM, ProdLDA) struggle to condition topics on sentiment or other semantic labels in an end-to-end trainable fashion, especially when discrete sampling is involved. While recent works have explored Gumbel-Softmax or reparameterization tricks for discrete approximations, they often fail to preserve the geometric structure of topic distributions or introduce bias in gradient estimation. Inspired by Paper 2’s idea of making discrete channels behave like noisy continuous ones for backpropagation, I propose a novel mechanism: treating topic-word distribution sampling as a *neural transport process* under sentiment conditioning. This approach leverages optimal transport principles to define a differentiable path between latent topic representations and observed words, where sentiment acts as a control variable shaping the transport cost. Unlike traditional fusion methods (Paper 1) that modify architecture or loss functions post-hoc, our method integrates sentiment at the generative level—guiding how probability mass is transported from topics to words. Furthermore, unlike activation boundary distillation (Paper 3), which focuses on neuron-level geometry, we focus on distributional geometry across vocabularies. The key innovation lies in formulating sentiment-conditioned transport plans as soft, learnable alignments optimized via backpropagation, enabling gradient flow from downstream sentiment classifiers all the way back to topic-word distributions. This allows joint optimization of topic coherence and sentiment discriminability—an elusive goal in prior work.

